alwaysApply: true
---

Parallel has two clearly separated user roles and a unified avatar system.
These behaviors are locked and must not be changed unless explicitly requested.

1. Role System (Owner vs Member)

Parallel has two roles:

Owner

The user who created the team/meeting.

Owners manage teams, generate rotations, and publish schedules.

Owner routes live under the main app routes.

Example owner routes:

/teams
/rotation
/schedule
/schedule/[scheduleId]
/schedule/[scheduleId]/analysis

Owners can:

create teams

invite members

generate rotations

publish schedules

Member

Members are users invited by the owner through the invite link.

Members:

submit availability

view schedules

cannot edit or regenerate schedules

Members must always use member routes, not owner routes.

Example member routes:

/member-dashboard
/member/schedule
/member/schedule/[scheduleId]

Members must never be redirected to owner dashboards.

Routing must always depend on team role, not billing plan.

2. Schedule Access Rules

Schedule viewing rules:

Owner:

Can access all schedules for teams they manage.

Member:

Can access schedules only if they belong to that team.

Member schedule pages must be read-only.

Members must NOT see:

publish buttons

regenerate buttons

editing tools

3. Avatar System (Global Sync)

Avatars must stay consistent across the entire application.

Avatar resolution priority:

member_submissions.avatar_url
→ profiles.avatar_url
→ auth.user_metadata.avatar_url
→ initials fallback

If avatar_url is null:

The UI must display the initials fallback avatar.

Example:

Rongerrrr → R
Zion Xu → ZX

The avatar component must never render an empty circle.

4. Avatar Editing Behavior

Profile editing allows:

Upload avatar

Replace avatar

Remove avatar

Removing an avatar must:

set avatar_url = null

After saving, all pages must update automatically:

navbar

schedule pages

team members

profile page

No page should cache stale avatar URLs.

5. Important Stability Rule

Do NOT change:

role routing logic

member vs owner route separation

avatar resolver priority

schedule permission rules

unless explicitly requested.

These systems are considered stable core architecture.
